NeighborVis has been developed and released as a software for community, service and research mining of multiple spatially connected data. The purpose of this software was to make investigations easier of questions important to a community, such as why is one park preferable to another, what to do with blighted streets, or why there is a variable spatial pattern in drug overdoses. To answer these and other activity, crime, health questions, software was needed that could synthesize multiple datasets, mining and visualizing them for context which might be buried deep within their structure, and connected by spatial location which would allow for easy mapping of the solution. Beneficiaries of this software could include a community action group wanting to understand the environment around potential neighborhood garden locations, a health and police department coordinating their efforts to address their overdose situation, or researchers from various non-spatial questions who are interested in the spatial pattern and interconnection between multiple data layers.

Intellectual Merit:

NeighborVis provides a new visual analytics system of geospatial data with rich semantic information in localized communities. The data consists of geospatial (longitude/latitude or locational address), time, and rich textual descriptions.

NeighborVis supports spatial-temporal data processing, management, query, and analytical reasoning facilitated by a newly design spatial semantic database and interactive visualization techniques. Users can easily query the community data with spatial-temporal constraints on the map, while simultaneously mining the associated attributes and comment fields for additional insights. In this way important concepts can be explored for a single location, or city block, mining all converging data on this area irrespective of field categories. For example, both health and police data often only mention overdose information deep within a reporting structure &ndash; NeighborVis could find these hidden patterns with these data. Potential uses include:
(1)    Social media data of geo-tagged twitter, Facebook, Instagram posts;
(2)    Real estate data with house price, buyer information, loan and other related documents;
(3)    Police data of crime reports with crime locations, involved personnel, and case details;
(4)    Public health data of epidemic disease cases with locations and descriptions;

Broader Impacts:

NeighborVis has been designed for maximum usability irrespective of academic discipline, professional background or education level. The search structures and visual / mapping displays are intuitive and allow the user to explore his/her data while combining other layers as they become available. As such, this software is useful for any individual or group interested in exploring data spatially &ndash; from neighborhood groups to the local mayor?s office, from parks and recreation to mosquito control.

NeighborVis can greatly help users from multiple sectors including academic institutions, business, finance, public services, non-profit organizations, and local governments by leveraging the advanced computation and visualization capabilities to utilize their large, complex, and rapidly accumulating community data. 



